<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> I didn't say that, Mauk2 did. No offense taken.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 None meant, regardless of who I was responding to (sorry for the misidentification).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I like a 3rd stage EPPP, we can use them to get a presence<br>
in space in the inner planets and the belt, when more efficient<br>
fusion drives become safe and reliable, the technology developed<br>
for a fission EPPP drive will cross over nicely with a ICAN style<br>
fusion drive.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 I'm confused or maybe we're mixing things up; Fusion, in the context of EPPP/NPR can mean a 2-stage bomb. Fission triggered fusion is required for pretty much anything over 10-15kt (correct?).<br>
The smaller, first generation NPR -the HLV lifted, space assembled ship- will probably use about 2kt, as the old 10 &amp; 20 meter ships called for, so they'll technically be fission.<br>
 A 2nd or 3rd generation, space built &quot;super&quot; -the space liner of tens of millions of tons we all salivate over- would probably use fission-fusion bombs since it'll need more power per pulse unit.<br>
 This still is the old &quot;bomb propelled ship&quot;. Nothing new here, except space resources going into the bulk of the behemoth.<br>
None of this requires anything beyond old-fashioned nuclear weaponeering (to put it bluntly. Granted there's a lot more finess involved!).<br>
<br>
ICAN is even a fission triggered fusion. It just doesn't use more than a few grams of fissionables per pulse (not a typical fission bomb to set it off). This might be used, if anti proton production and storage improve enough -I'd like to see the space infrastructure effort get enough economic clout to start anti proton production going up there. Not because I'm afraid of the antimatter getting loose and destroying the Earth, but just because it might be cheaper to do it if it can be done -closer to the end-use and plenty of cheap energy. This is way down the line, because of all the detail involved in this production; lots of small, detailed stuff to be lifted from Earth or built from factories in space. This takes a while to bootstrap up to.<br>
<br>
 I don't place any faith in any other fusion drive I've heard of, since we don't seem to have much idea of how to do it... Even ICAN uses a pusher plate &amp; shock absorbers to some extent: no real effort taken to confine the fusion, and it's not a controlled plasma -just a bang.<br>
