<br>
An ORION would have to be huge to require fission-fusion bombs, and by the time ships of that size are built, I believe that an idea like ICAN (which is still EPPP, again I should be more specific), which achieves higher Isp for size, will be usible. True it uses fission, but the expendible pellets dont require the precise engineering as expendible pulse units. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 112<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/24/02 11:29:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=197.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: acceptability of NPR and other points</span><hr size=1> John Fraz: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  Even ICAN uses a pusher plate &amp; shock absorbers to some extent: no real effort taken to confine the fusion, and it's not a controlled plasma -just a bang. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sure!  To my mind, ICANN is basically an Orion, dressed up in a fancy outfit.  <br>
<br>
Now, it is a GOOD fancy outfit, don't get me wrong!  <br>
<br>
ICANN has major advances over Orion on two fronts:  Pulse unit ignition/efficiency and energy coupling.<br>
<br>
Pulse unit ignition/efficiency:  ICANN fuel pellets are triggered by anti-protons generating neutrons in annihilatory collisions with U238.  So many fast neutrons are generated that the U238 shell is essentially fissioned instantly, and inertial confinement principals then allow the DT fusion fuel to be lit off with MUCH smaller amounts of fissiles.  Efficient pellets means less mass in the pulse units per unit of energy.  Since the fuel pellets also have very small yields, much smaller pusher plates can effectively utilized, since the smaller pulse units can be exploded much closer.<br>
<br>
Energy coupling: Unlike the Orion, which used a durable pusher plate and coupled the pulse unit to the ship with momentum transfer, the ICANN -II uses an ablative &quot;thrust shell&quot; which is coupled to the pulse units with radiative transfer.<br>
<br>
In other words, the ICANN-II uses photons from the pulse units to heat a thin layer of the thrust shell into a superhot plasma, which then boils off at crazy speeds.  I feel this is much superior, because the energy transfer is much quicker than with Orion.  This means radial shockwaves (the worst problem for Orion I feel) are avoided.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/25/02 7:45:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=197.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Antimater Production.</span><hr size=1> The total world production of antimatter is about 10 nanograms a year. Some nitpickers say that antimatter can't be produced in the required amounts for a space propulsion system for two reasons, cost and the energy required to make it, I say bull----.<br>
<br>
What antimatter costs to make today is anybody’s guess. However if we decided to spend the required amount of cash to develop an industrial process to make antimatter we could produce enough for space exploration. when you consider just how potent antimatter is as a fuel the cost of it would be reasonable. If we could make 5 grams of antimatter a year that would be more than enough to conduct a vigorous interplanetary exploration program. That 5 grams of anti-hydrogen when brought into contact with an equal amount of hydrogen would release as much energy as 220,000,000 pounds of LOX and H2 <br>
<br>
When we first started to produce plutonium in the 1940’s the cost per gram was approximately 5,000,000 – 7,000,000 in 1998 dollars. Of course once the infrastructure was in place the cost rapidly dropped to a level where the stuff had a commercial use. On another note in the 18th century Aluminum was a precious metal and second to none in price per ounce, today it is dirt cheap. It is dirt cheap because we have the infrastructure and an efficient industrial process to make it in mass quantities. <br>
<br>
When I as a kid I saw a propulsion scheme that used tiny amounts antimatter to boost the performance of large rather conventional looking rockets. The text of the article explained that 0.00005 gram/sec of antimatter would be shot into the engines reaction chamber along with 100kg's liquid H2 as reaction mass. The resulting combustion was to release a force equal to burning 1000kg Lox and H2 per second. <br>
<br>
The illustration of the engine showed a diagram of how this engine was to be cooled. The text of the article said that along with circulating liquid H2 through the engine Liquid H2 would also be pumped through thousands of tiny holes drilled into the interior walls of the combustion chamber and throat to form a film of hydrogen gas that would transport excess heat out of the engine. I have no idea what the thrust or -ISP was supposed to be but the idea looked interesting at the time. They also mentioned that the interior walls of the engine were to be made of tungsten. <br>
<br>
Note: I could be wrong about how much antimatter was to be delivered per second but that’s the figure that popped into my head when I recalled the article.<br>
<br>
Nuke Pulse<br>
<br>
<br>
Another antimatter article:<br>
